subsection.p:
So a small eastward step raises the canopy at about
\frac{11}{50}
meter per meter, while a small northward step lowers it at about
\frac7{25}
meter per meter.

The tangent plane to the graph z=A(x,y) at (3,2,A(3,2)) is

  \boxed{
  z=
  \frac{129}{20}
  +
  \frac{11}{50}(x-3)
  -
  \frac7{25}(y-2).
  }

statement.p:
What is the differential
df_{\mathbf p}
as an object? What does it eat, and what does it return?

Why does the function
f(x,y)= \begin{cases} \dfrac{xy}{x^2+y^2}, \amp (x,y)\ne(0,0),\\[2mm] 0, \amp (x,y)=(0,0) \end{cases}
show that partial derivatives at a point do not even guarantee continuity?

Why does the function
g(x,y)= \begin{cases} \dfrac{x^2y}{x^2+y^2}, \amp (x,y)\ne(0,0),\\[2mm] 0, \amp (x,y)=(0,0) \end{cases}
show that continuity plus partial derivatives at a point still does not guarantee differentiability?

Let
f(x,y)= \begin{cases} \dfrac{x^2y}{x^2+y^2}, \amp (x,y)\ne(0,0),\\[2mm] 0, \amp (x,y)=(0,0). \end{cases}
Show that f_x(0,0)=0 and f_y(0,0)=0. Then use the path y=x to show that f is not differentiable at the origin.

Let
f(x,y)= \begin{cases} x^2\sin\left(\dfrac1x\right), \amp x\ne0,\\[2mm] 0, \amp x=0. \end{cases}
This function does not depend on y. Show that it is differentiable at (0,0), but that f_x is not continuous at (0,0).

introduction.p:
The base operating point is
(T,p,s)=(22,60,30).
At this point,
O_T=-0.18,\qquad O_p=0.035,\qquad O_s=-0.025.
So

  \boxed{
  dO_{(22,60,30)}
  =
  -0.18\,dT+0.035\,dp-0.025\,ds.
  }

statement.p:
Define
f(x,y)= \begin{cases} \dfrac{x^3}{x^2+y^2}, \amp (x,y)\ne(0,0),\\[2mm] 0, \amp (x,y)=(0,0). \end{cases}
Show that the directional derivative D_{\mathbf u}f(0,0) exists for every unit vector \mathbf u=(a,b). Then show that the function is not differentiable at the origin.

Someone claims that the graph of
f(x,y)= \begin{cases} \dfrac{x^2y}{x^2+y^2}, \amp (x,y)\ne(0,0),\\[2mm] 0, \amp (x,y)=(0,0) \end{cases}
has tangent plane z=0 at the origin because f_x(0,0)=0,\qquad f_y(0,0)=0. Write a short response explaining exactly why this reasoning fails.
